The article discusses the importance of achieving equal pay for women in the United States. It highlights that Equal Pay Day, which marks the day when women catch up to men's earnings from the previous year, falls on March 15 this year, the earliest it has ever been. Despite progress, the article emphasizes that there is still work to be done, as women, especially women of color, continue to face significant pay disparities. The Biden-Harris Administration is committed to addressing these barriers and has taken steps to advance equal pay, including issuing an Executive Order and raising the minimum wage for federal contractors. The administration is also advocating for the passage of the Paycheck Fairness Act and legislation that would lower the cost of child care and elder care. The article concludes by calling on all Americans to recognize the value of women's skills and contributions and join efforts to achieve equal pay.